1. Assessment Objectives
AO	What It Tests	How to Demonstrate
AO1: Knowledge & Understanding	Accurate knowledge of political institutions, processes, concepts, theories, thinkers, and issues	Use precise political terminology, name specific Acts/cases/events/dates, reference political thinkers and their ideas accurately
AO2: Analysis	Explaining why and how, making connections, identifying similarities/differences, building a logical argument	Don't just describe — explain the significance, causes, and consequences. Make synoptic links between specification areas where relevant
AO3: Evaluation	Constructing balanced arguments, making substantiated judgements, weighing competing perspectives, reaching reasoned conclusions	Argue both sides, assess the strength of arguments, provide a sustained line of reasoning, conclude with a justified verdict
AO Weightings by Question Type
Question	AO1	AO2	AO3	Total
9-mark	3 marks	6 marks	—	9 marks
25-mark (essay)	5 marks	10 marks	10 marks	25 marks
25-mark (extract)	5 marks	10 marks	10 marks	25 marks
Critical insight: AO1 (knowledge) is only worth 5/25 marks on essays. The bulk of marks come from AO2 (analysis) and AO3 (evaluation). You must go beyond describing — you must explain WHY things matter and EVALUATE competing arguments.

