3. 9-Mark Questions
What the Mark Scheme Says
AO1 (3 marks): Accurate, detailed knowledge with precise political terminology and relevant examples
AO2 (6 marks): Developed, focused analysis that explains WHY/HOW factors operate, directly addressing the question
No AO3: You do NOT need to evaluate or reach a conclusion. Pure knowledge + analysis.
Structure: 3 paragraphs, 3 distinct points. No introduction. No conclusion.
Paragraph	Content
1	Point → Explain with political terminology → Example (specific, dated, named) → Analyse the significance/impact
2	Second distinct point → Explain → Example → Analyse
3	Third distinct point → Explain → Example → Analyse
Critical Rules
Exactly 3 points — the examiner marks only the first 3 points you make. Writing more wastes time.
No introduction or conclusion — start your first point immediately
Each paragraph must contain analysis (AO2) — don't just describe, explain WHY it matters
Use precise, contemporary examples — specific Acts, dates, cases, events, political figures
Equal weight — each paragraph should be roughly the same length
Model Answer
Explain and analyse three ways in which the UK constitution has been reformed since 1997. [9 marks]

Paragraph 1 (Devolution): One major constitutional reform since 1997 has been devolution. The Scotland Act 1998 established the Scottish Parliament with legislative powers over devolved matters such as health, education, and policing. The Government of Wales Act 1998 and the Northern Ireland Act 1998 similarly created devolved assemblies. This has fundamentally altered the UK's traditionally unitary system, dispersing power away from Westminster and creating what many describe as a quasi-federal structure. The significance of this reform is demonstrated by the fact that the Scottish Parliament has used its powers to pursue distinctive policies, such as abolishing tuition fees, showing that devolution has created meaningful policy divergence across the UK.

Paragraph 2 (Human Rights Act 1998): A second reform was the incorporation of the European Convention on Human Rights into domestic law through the Human Rights Act 1998. Prior to this, UK citizens had to take cases to the European Court of Human Rights in Strasbourg; the HRA allowed rights to be enforced in domestic courts. This strengthened the judiciary's constitutional role, as courts gained the power to issue "declarations of incompatibility" when legislation conflicted with Convention rights, as seen in the Belmarsh case (2004) where indefinite detention without trial was declared incompatible with Article 5. This reform shifted the balance of power between the executive and judiciary, giving judges a greater role in protecting individual liberties and acting as a check on government.

Paragraph 3 (House of Lords Reform): A third reform was the House of Lords Act 1999, which removed all but 92 hereditary peers from the House of Lords. This was intended to modernise the second chamber and increase its democratic legitimacy by reducing the influence of an unelected aristocratic element. The removal of hereditary peers has arguably made the Lords more assertive in scrutinising government legislation, as life peers — many of whom are policy experts — feel greater confidence in challenging the Commons. For example, the Lords defeated the government over 100 times during the 2005–10 Parliament. This reform demonstrates an ongoing — and still incomplete — process of constitutional modernisation, as the Lords remains an unelected chamber.

