4. 25-Mark Essay Questions (No Extract)
What the Mark Scheme Says
AO1 (5 marks): Detailed, accurate knowledge and understanding of relevant political concepts, institutions, processes, and theories
AO2 (10 marks): Balanced, developed analysis that is consistently focused on the question, with well-selected and relevant examples
AO3 (10 marks): Sustained, logical argument leading to a substantiated, reasoned conclusion. Must demonstrate evaluation of competing perspectives throughout
Structure: Introduction + 3–4 main body paragraphs + conclusion
Section	Content	Time
Introduction (3–4 sentences)	Define key terms, directly address the question, state your thesis (overall argument), briefly signpost	~2 min
Body ¶1	Argument FOR the statement → evidence/example → explain significance → evaluate strength of argument	~6 min
Body ¶2	Counter-argument AGAINST → evidence/example → explain → evaluate	~6 min
Body ¶3	Second argument FOR or a different perspective → evidence → explain → evaluate	~6 min
Body ¶4 (optional)	Additional factor / nuance / synoptic link	~4 min
Conclusion (4–5 sentences)	Synthesise arguments → restate thesis → provide final "knockout" judgement → do NOT introduce new material	~3 min
Paragraph Structure: PEEE (for each body paragraph)
Step	Action	Example
P — Point	State a clear factor/argument that answers the question	"One reason the PM is considered the most powerful figure in UK politics is..."
E — Evidence	Provide specific, dated, named examples	"...as demonstrated by Tony Blair's decision to commit the UK to the Iraq War in 2003 without a formal Commons vote at the time..."
E — Explain	Explain WHY this evidence supports your point — this is analysis (AO2)	"...this illustrates the extent of prime ministerial prerogative powers in foreign policy, which bypass normal parliamentary oversight..."
E — Evaluate	Assess the strength/limitation of this argument — this is evaluation (AO3)	"...however, the significance of this power has diminished since the 2003 convention, as subsequent PMs have sought parliamentary approval for military action, suggesting that political constraints now limit the PM's freedom even where legal authority exists."
Model Answer
Evaluate the view that the UK Parliament is no longer able to effectively hold the government to account. [25 marks]

Introduction: Parliamentary accountability — the principle that the executive must answer to the legislature for its actions — is a cornerstone of the UK's representative democracy. While Parliament possesses numerous formal mechanisms to scrutinise the government, including select committees, Prime Minister's Questions, and opposition day debates, the question of whether these mechanisms are genuinely effective in an era of strong party discipline and executive dominance is a matter of significant debate. This essay will argue that while Parliament retains some meaningful tools for accountability, the dominance of the executive — particularly when supported by a large Commons majority — significantly undermines its effectiveness.

Body ¶1 (Parliament IS effective — select committees): One way in which Parliament continues to hold the government to account is through the select committee system. Select committees, strengthened by the Wright Reforms of 2010 which introduced elected chairs, have become increasingly assertive in scrutinising government policy and expenditure. For example, the Health and Social Care Committee, chaired by Jeremy Hunt, conducted a high-profile investigation into the government's handling of the Covid-19 pandemic, producing a report in 2021 that criticised delays in implementing lockdowns. The elected chairs now carry greater legitimacy and independence, making them less susceptible to government pressure. Select committees can summon ministers and civil servants, request documents, and publish reports that generate significant media attention, placing public pressure on the government. However, select committees have no binding power — the government is not legally obligated to implement their recommendations. The Covid-19 inquiry report, for instance, led to public discussion but no formal policy reversal, suggesting that committee influence remains persuasive rather than decisive.

Body ¶2 (Parliament is NOT effective — party discipline): Conversely, the effectiveness of parliamentary scrutiny is significantly undermined by the party whip system. The whips enforce party discipline by controlling career advancement and threatening deselection, meaning that backbench MPs are often reluctant to vote against their own government. This severely weakens the Commons' ability to function as a genuine check on executive power. For example, during the 2019–2024 Conservative government with a majority of 80 seats, the whips were generally able to ensure that legislation passed with minimal backbench rebellion, even on contentious measures such as the Nationality and Borders Act 2022. The payroll vote — approximately 100 government-appointed MPs who are bound by collective responsibility — further reduces the number of potential critics. This suggests that for much of the time, the Commons acts as a rubber stamp for government policy rather than an independent scrutinising body. However, it should be noted that significant rebellions do occur on matters of conscience or extreme policy disagreement, as demonstrated by the 99 Conservative MPs who rebelled against the government's Covid-19 Plan B restrictions in December 2021, showing that party discipline has limits.

Body ¶3 (Parliament IS effective — House of Lords): The House of Lords also plays an important role in holding the government to account. As the Lords is not dominated by the governing party and contains a significant proportion of crossbench peers, it is often more willing to challenge government legislation. The Lords defeated the government 128 times during the 2017–19 Parliament alone, forcing significant amendments to the Brexit Withdrawal Bill. The expertise of many life peers — former judges, academics, diplomats, and business leaders — means that Lords scrutiny often identifies technical flaws in legislation that the Commons, dominated by career politicians under the whip, fails to catch. However, the effectiveness of the Lords is limited by its democratic weakness: as an unelected chamber, its legitimacy to challenge the elected Commons is contested. The Salisbury Convention means the Lords will not block manifesto commitments, and the Parliament Acts of 1911 and 1949 allow the Commons to override Lords opposition after a delay.

Body ¶4 (Executive dominance): More broadly, the structural dominance of the executive in the UK system means that Parliament is inherently disadvantaged. The fusion of powers — whereby the PM and Cabinet are drawn from and sit in Parliament — means that the government controls the legislative timetable, determines which bills are debated, and can use devices such as programme motions to limit debate time. This stands in contrast to a separation of powers system like the USA, where Congress controls its own agenda. The government's control of information also undermines accountability: ministers can refuse to answer questions at PMQs or provide evasive responses, and the culture of ministerial responsibility has weakened, as ministers increasingly survive scandals that would previously have prompted resignations.

Conclusion: In conclusion, while Parliament retains formal mechanisms for accountability — particularly through an increasingly assertive select committee system and an independent House of Lords — the effectiveness of these mechanisms is severely constrained by the structural dominance of the executive and the party whip system. Parliament is most effective as an accountability mechanism when the government has a small or no majority, as demonstrated during the 2017–19 Parliament when Theresa May's minority government suffered historic defeats, including the largest government defeat in history on her Brexit deal in January 2019. When the government commands a large majority, as seen in 2019–24, parliamentary scrutiny becomes significantly weaker. Therefore, the effectiveness of parliamentary accountability is contingent on the political context — specifically, the size of the government's majority and the willingness of backbenchers to defy the whip — rather than being a fixed feature of the constitution.

5. 25-Mark Extract Questions
What the Mark Scheme Says
Same AO split as the no-extract essay (AO1: 5, AO2: 10, AO3: 10), BUT you are additionally assessed on your ability to:

Explicitly reference the extract — quote short phrases and analyse their meaning
Engage with the extract's arguments — support, challenge, or contextualise them using your own knowledge
Use the extract as a springboard, not a summary — do NOT just paraphrase the extract
Structure: Same as the 25-mark essay, but with extract integration
Section	Content
Introduction	Define terms, state thesis, briefly acknowledge the extract's position
Body ¶1	Use a point FROM the extract → quote a short phrase → analyse using your own knowledge → evaluate
Body ¶2	Challenge or develop an extract argument → add your own evidence → analyse → evaluate
Body ¶3	Introduce an argument NOT in the extract (your own knowledge) → evidence → analyse → evaluate
Body ¶4 (optional)	Further point or synoptic link
Conclusion	Synthesise → final judgement
How to Use the Extract Effectively
Do ✅	Don't ❌
Quote short phrases: "The extract argues that the PM is 'first among equals'..."	Copy out long passages from the extract
Analyse the quote: "This phrase suggests that the PM's power is derived from cabinet support, which can be withdrawn..."	Simply paraphrase what the extract says without adding your own analysis
Challenge the extract: "However, the extract's characterisation overlooks the PM's power of patronage..."	Treat the extract as fact — you must critically engage with it
Integrate your own knowledge to support/contradict extract claims	Write an answer that ignores the extract entirely
Use the extract in 2–3 paragraphs, but also include your own independent arguments	Use the extract in every single paragraph — you need to show independent knowledge too
Model Answer (Abbreviated)
Extract: "The Supreme Court has become the most significant check on executive power in the UK. Its rulings, such as Miller I (2017) and Miller II (2019), have directly constrained government actions and asserted the sovereignty of Parliament."

Analyse, evaluate, and compare the arguments in the extract about the role of the Supreme Court. [25 marks]

Introduction: The role of the UK Supreme Court, established by the Constitutional Reform Act 2005 and operational from 2009, as a check on executive power is a subject of considerable constitutional debate. The extract argues that the Supreme Court has become "the most significant check on executive power," citing the landmark Miller cases. While there is substantial evidence to support this view, this essay will argue that the Supreme Court is one of several important checks, and that its effectiveness is constrained by parliamentary sovereignty and the political context in which it operates.

Body ¶1 (Supporting the extract): The extract's claim that the Supreme Court "has directly constrained government actions" is well supported by the Miller II (2019) ruling. In R (Miller) v The Prime Minister, the Supreme Court unanimously ruled that Boris Johnson's prorogation of Parliament was unlawful, null, and of no effect. This was an extraordinary ruling that directly overturned an exercise of the royal prerogative by the Prime Minister... (Continue with analysis of significance and evaluation of whether this makes the Court "the most significant" check)

Body ¶2 (Challenging the extract): However, the extract's characterisation of the Supreme Court as "the most significant check" on executive power is arguably an overstatement. The Court's power is fundamentally constrained by parliamentary sovereignty... (Continue with evidence of limitations — no power to strike down legislation, declarations of incompatibility are non-binding, political backlash)

Body ¶3 (Own knowledge — alternative checks): Furthermore, the extract overlooks the role of other institutions that arguably provide more consistent and routine checks on executive power. Select committees, the House of Lords, and the media all play daily scrutiny roles... (Compare with Supreme Court's sporadic intervention)

Conclusion: In conclusion, while the extract is correct that the Miller cases represent significant judicial interventions, describing the Supreme Court as "the most significant check" overstates its role...

