8. Key Exam Technique Rules
Universal Rules
Use precise political terminology — "parliamentary sovereignty" not "Parliament is in charge"; "prerogative powers" not "PM's special powers"
Name specific examples with dates — "the Scotland Act 1998" not "devolution legislation"; "Miller II (2019)" not "a Supreme Court case"
Every paragraph must analyse (AO2) — explain WHY/HOW, not just WHAT
Sustained evaluation throughout (for 25-markers) — don't save all evaluation for the conclusion. Each body paragraph should contain evaluation
Answer the exact question — if it says "to what extent," your conclusion must state a degree; if it asks about "the most important," you must compare factors
Be contemporary — use the most recent examples available. A 2024 example is worth more than a 1997 example (though historical context remains important)
Balance — genuinely engage with both sides. Don't write three paragraphs agreeing and one token "however" paragraph
Common Evaluation Techniques
Technique	Example
"It depends on..."	"The PM's power depends on the size of their majority, their personal authority, and the political context"
Short-term vs long-term	"In the short term, devolution increased democratic participation; in the long term, it may threaten the unity of the UK"
Context-dependent	"Parliament's effectiveness varies between minority and majority government scenarios"
Competing perspectives	"Pluralists would argue pressure groups enhance democracy; elitists would counter that wealthy groups have disproportionate influence"
Synoptic links	"This connects to the debate about parliamentary sovereignty — if Parliament is sovereign, can the Supreme Court truly be described as the most significant check?"
Comparative	"The US Supreme Court has the power of constitutional judicial review, making it arguably a more effective check than its UK counterpart"
Timing Strategy
Question	Time	Strategy
Reading time	5 min	Read all questions, choose your Section C essay
9-marker ×3	30 min (10 each)	Write immediately — no plan needed. 3 paragraphs, 3 points
25-mark extract	30 min	3 min planning, 25 min writing, 2 min checking
