Common Mistakes to Avoid
Mistake	Why It Costs Marks
Writing 4+ points on a 9-marker	Examiner only marks the first 3 — you waste time
No conclusion on a 25-marker	You cannot access Level 5 without a substantiated conclusion
Paraphrasing the extract instead of analysing it	Shows no independent analysis (AO2)
Generic examples ("the government does X")	Must be specific: "Boris Johnson's prorogation in August 2019"
Only describing, not explaining WHY	Description = AO1 only. Analysis (WHY/HOW) = AO2, which is worth double
All arguments on one side	Cannot access "balanced" at Level 5
Introduction longer than 4 sentences	Wastes time — no marks for lengthy introductions
Introducing new material in the conclusion	The conclusion should synthesise existing arguments, not add new ones
9. Quick-Use Instructions for AI Models
When answering an AQA A-Level Politics question:

Identify the question type — 9-mark or 25-mark? Extract-based or essay?
For 9-markers: Write exactly 3 paragraphs. No introduction, no conclusion. Each paragraph: Point → Explain → Specific example (named, dated) → Analyse significance. Stop after 3 points.
For 25-mark essays: Introduction (thesis + define terms) → 3–4 body paragraphs (PEEE: Point, Evidence, Explain, Evaluate) → Conclusion (synthesise + knockout judgement). Ensure BALANCE — arguments on both sides.
For 25-mark extract questions: Same structure as essay, BUT explicitly quote short phrases from the extract, analyse them, and challenge/support them with your own knowledge. Use the extract in 2–3 paragraphs; also include at least 1 paragraph of entirely independent knowledge.
ALWAYS use precise political terminology — parliamentary sovereignty, prerogative powers, judicial review, collective ministerial responsibility, etc.
ALWAYS provide specific, named, dated examples — "the Fixed-term Parliaments Act 2011 (repealed 2022)" not "a law about elections"
ALWAYS evaluate in every body paragraph (for 25-markers) — don't save evaluation for the conclusion. Each paragraph should assess the strength of the argument.
Use contemporary examples — reference recent events, elections, court cases, and legislation wherever possible
For Paper 3 (Political Ideas): Reference specific thinkers by name (Locke, Burke, Marx, etc.) and explain how their ideas connect to the question. Compare thinkers within and across ideologies.
Word count targets: 9-marker ≈ 250–350 words. 25-marker ≈ 800–1000 words. Quality over quantity — a focused 800-word essay beats a rambling 1200-word one.
